Question Text: What is the most common warehouse error you encounter (e.g., mispicks, under-picks, over-picks, receive parts for different dealer, etc.)?
Response: In my opinion there should be a 5th item which is vendor  responsibility for shoddy packaging. Its inexcusable for hvac blower units to ship in a cardboard box with a couple of thin foam sheets and the box is large enough for the part to move around during shipment. Parts packaged in this manner dont survive well in air and ground shipments.  Theres an additonal layer to this where the PDC employee should be cognizant that if the part they are packaging is going to be shipped cross country to package the part in a manner thats going to prevent the part from being damaged in transit.

Question Text: What three product types tend to have the most damages to the packaging?
Response: Any bulky heavy item in a cardboard box. If it is shipped via Fedex air or ground its going to come in rough. Axles, struts, cats. Anything where the box has enough space with the part inside to move around in shipment is going to come in with damaged packaging.

Response: Heavier parts such as hubs and compressors tend to puncture the box often, but don't always lead to damaged parts. Some older bumpers that are wrapped in the older bubble wrap will come in with micro tears that can lead to damage, but once again, not always. Lastly, but most importantly, parts that have been returned to the PDC as new, unused parts more often than not come to me in absolutely horrific condition. Some of the boxes are held together with tape alone, where you can clearly see the part inside to closed box through the tape. This always leads me to question the integrity of the part, the dealership who returned it to the PDC, and the warehouse personnel who thought it a good idea to credit that dealership for the return and place it back on the shelf as usable stock.

Question Text: What three product types tend to have the most damages to the product?
Response: Bumpers often come in warped or damaged even though the outer packaging is intact. This leads me to believe that they are being wrapped up with the damage already there. Also, some of the heavier parts such as the compressors move around in their boxes and break the small, plastic connector attached to it. And, again, I get part returned parts as new parts that come in already damaged from other dealerships.

Question Text: What is the most common warehouse error you encounter (e.g., mispicks, under-picks, over-picks, receive parts for different dealer, etc.)?
Response: Shortages, or under-picks, tend to be the most common warehouse error. A lot of the time, they will take multiple packs out of the main plastic bag (ex: drain plug gaskets come in smaller packages of 10 but in a main bag of 100) and put them back into the main bag even though the count is now less than the 100. Instead of counting the packs of 10, the warehouse puller assumes the count of 100 on the outer bag is correct even though it is opened and actually short.
